ss the pain they solve is concrete and demonstrated\n\n## What's been done\n\nComprehensive technology research covering command runners, agent instruction standards, architecture documentation patterns, and lessons from industry practice.\n\n**Artifact**: `.agent/work-plans/RESEARCH_ISSUE-249.md` on branch `claude/research-issue-technologies-70lUL`\n\nThis research informs the guiding principles above and should be consulted when making specific tool or pattern choices.\n\n## What's next\n\nPick the highest-pain problem, fix it, repeat — with each fix evaluated against the vision and principles above. Candidate starting points (not ordered yet):\n\n- [ ] Distill research into a short decision summary that can be referenced without re-reading 2,500 lines\n- [ ] Recover the intent behind existing scripts and Makefile targets (what problem does each solve?), then redesign a simpler set of tools that preserves those intents — capturing the design rationale as ADRs\n- [ ] Establish ADRs to capture the design decisions that already exist implicitly (per-framework duplication, worktree isolation, workspace/project boundary, etc.)\n- [ ] Simplify the Makefile or replace with a clearer interface\n- [ ] Create AGENTS.md as the shared instruction layer\n- [ ] Consolidate and reduce documentation overlap\n- [ ] Align CLAUDE.md with the \"map not encyclopedia\" pattern (~150 lines pointing to topic files)\n\nAs tasks are completed, new ones will emerge. This issue tracks the overall direction; individual tasks get their own issues.\n\n## Related issues\n\nThe research cross-references several open issues that overlap with this effort (§9). As work progresses, those issues may be absorbed, closed as duplicates, or kept as independent tasks that align with the direction here.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1772034786,"nonce":"Qc07/nqKPY6RElayYZMzTU5bz58=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lAHOQ241x87so-6xzqX1LLc"},"target":"efb04c7efcf7f3b3327b856768c4da222682c6df50c82b27a8a34893f0240148","message":"## Problem\n\nThis workspace has grown through many small, isolated fixes. Each solved a real problem, but without a shared direction the result is accumulated complexity: overlapping scripts, duplicated documentation, and design decisions buried in issue comments where they get accidentally reverted.\n\nThe fix isn't a comprehensive redesign — it's establishing the direction that was missing, then improving incrementally with that direction guiding each step.\n\n## Vision\n\nA workspace that is:\n- **Simple to use** — a small number of clear entry points, not 42 scripts\n- **Self-documenting** — the structure and tooling explain themselves\n- **Durable** — design decisions are captured where they won't be lost or silently reverted\n- **Sustainable** — improvements continue naturally, not as periodic large rework efforts\n\n## Guiding principles\n\nThese should inform every change, not just this effort:\n\n1. **Workspace vs. project separation** — workspace infrastructure is generic ROS 2 tooling; project-specific content belongs in project repos\n2. **Per-framework instruction files are intentional** — different agent frameworks benefit from different layouts; don't consolidate them into one file\n3. **AGENTS.md as shared layer** — common instructions go in a cross-framework file; framework-specific files contain only overrides\n4. **Capture decisions, not just implementations** — ADRs or equivalent so future agents and humans know *why*, not just *what*\n5. **Enforcement over documentation** — rules that matter must be enforced mechanically (CI, hooks, branch protection), not just written down\n6. **Radical simplicity** — resist adding process, files, or tools unless the pain they solve is concrete and demonstrated\n\n## What's been done\n\n### Research (3,019 lines, 6 appendices)\n\nComprehensive technology research on `feature/issue-249` at `.agent/work-plans/RESEARCH_ISSUE-249.md`. Covers command runners, AGENTS.md standard, script consolidation, documentation patterns, architecture lifecycle, workspace/project boundary, and cross-references with 21 open issues. Appendices analyze Osmani's spec-driven development article, a 60+ tool landscape scan, GitHub Spec Kit, OpenAI's harness engineering at 1M LOC scale, and multi-agent engineering patterns from GitHub's failure analysis.\n\nThe research is a reference document — not meant to be read end-to-end. Agents consult relevant sections during specific subtasks, since each task needs a different perspective on the material.\n\nMerged via [PR #255](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/pull/255).\n\n### Architecture Decision Records\n\nFour foundational ADRs established in `docs/decisions/`, capturing design decisions that previously existed only in issue comments and commit history:\n- ADR-0001: Adopt Architecture Decision Records\n- ADR-0002: Worktree isolation over branch switching\n- ADR-0003: Workspace infrastructure is project-agnostic\n- ADR-0004: Enforcement hierarchy for agent compliance\n\nMerged via [PR #253](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/pull/253) (sub-issue [#251](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/251)).\n\n### Script and Makefile intent recovery\n\nDocumented the purpose and design intent behind existing scripts and Makefile targets, as input for the interface redesign.\n\nMerged via [PR #254](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/pull/254) (sub-issue [#252](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/252)).\n\n## What's next\n\nRemaining work falls into two categories: items ready to execute (clear scope, no design ambiguity) and items needing discussion first (competing principles, design trade-offs, or tool choices that affect daily workflow).\n\n### Ready to execute\n\nThese can proceed as sub-issues without further #249-level discussion:\n\n- [ ] **Create PR template** — `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md` with architecture impact checklist. The research has a concrete template (§7e). Straightforward, no design decisions.\n- [ ] **Close sub-issues [#251](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/251) and [#252](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/252)** — work is merged into the feature branch.\n\n### Needs discussion before executing\n\nThese involve trade-offs between guiding principles or tool choices that should be resolved — potentially as new ADRs — before implementation begins:\n\n- [ ] **Enforcement: Claude Code hooks vs. framework-agnostic layers** — Hooks (§F6) are a fast win for enforcement (worktree guards, commit validation), but they're Claude Code-specific. Guiding principle #5 says enforce mechanically, but #2 and #3 say keep framework-specific content minimal. Should enforcement live in hooks (fast, vendor-locked), CI/pre-commit (framework-agnostic, slower feedback), MCP servers (cross-agent, higher effort), or a layered combination? This is ADR-worthy — the answer shapes all future enforcement work.\n\n- [ ] **Create AGENTS.md as the shared instruction layer** — The concept is clear (principle #3), but the content split needs deliberation: what moves from CLAUDE.md to AGENTS.md, what stays framework-specific? Should the Always/Ask/Never taxonomy (§D5) be adopted during creation or as a separate step? What about the other framework instruction files (copilot-instructions.md, gemini-cli instructions, AI_RULES.md) — which get replaced, which get reduced to overrides?\n\n- [ ] **Restructure CLAUDE.md as \"map not encyclopedia\"** — Tightly coupled with AGENTS.md creation. What gets extracted into `.agent/knowledge/` topic files, what goes into AGENTS.md, what stays? The 150-line target from OpenAI's experience (§E3) is a reference point, but our multi-repo complexity may need more. Requires a line-by-line triage of the current file.\n\n- [ ] **Simplify Makefile or replace with `just`** — The research recommends `just` (§1a), but this is a tool choice that adds a new dependency and affects daily workflow. The `just-mcp` angle (§F2.3) adds a consideration: it would make workspace commands accessible to any MCP-compatible agent. But the current Makefile with self-documenting patterns (§2) may be sufficient if the team prefers zero new dependencies.\n\n- [ ] **Consolidate and reduce documentation overlap** — Depends on what happens with AGENTS.md and CLAUDE.md restructuring. The 24 markdown files have documented overlaps (§5), but the consolidation strategy flows from the AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md design decisions above. Can't be done independently.\n\n- [ ] **Evaluate MCP servers for ROS 2 workflows** — ROSBag MCP server, ROS 2 Robot Control MCP server, and potentially a custom workspace MCP server (§F2.3). Less a design question, more a \"is this useful for our actual workflow\" question. Depends on whether bag files and runtime inspection are part of the development loop.\n\n### How discussion items proceed\n\nEach discussion item should be resolved through conversation (on this issue or dedicated sub-issues). When a decision is reached, capture it as an ADR and then create a sub-issue for implementation. The enforcement hooks question is the most foundational — it affects several other items.\n\n## Related issues\n\nThe research cross-references several open issues that overlap with this effort (§9). As work progresses, those issues may be absorbed, closed as duplicates, or kept as independent tasks that align with the direction here.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1772035627,"nonce":"QBPuh2lU2gbxoloFPO4/H4TtSOs=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lAHOQ241x87so-6xzqX2HNM"},"target":"efb04c7efcf7f3b3327b856768c4da222682c6df50c82b27a8a34893f0240148","message":"## Problem\n\nThis workspace has grown through many small, isolated fixes. Each solved a real problem, but without a shared direction the result is accumulated complexity: overlapping scripts, duplicated documentation, and design decisions buried in issue comments where they get accidentally reverted.\n\nThe fix isn't a comprehensive redesign — it's establishing the direction that was missing, then improving incrementally with that direction guiding each step.\n\n## Vision\n\nA workspace that is:\n- **Simple to use** — a small number of clear entry points, not 42 scripts\n- **Self-documenting** — the structure and tooling explain themselves\n- **Durable** — design decisions are captured where they won't be lost or silently reverted\n- **Sustainable** — improvements continue naturally, not as periodic large rework efforts\n\n## Guiding principles\n\nThese should inform every change, not just this effort:\n\n1. **Workspace vs. project separation** — workspace infrastructure is generic ROS 2 tooling; project-specific content belongs in project repos\n2. **Per-framework instruction files are intentional** — different agent frameworks benefit from different layouts; don't consolidate them into one file\n3. **Primary framework first, portability where free** — use the full capabilities of the active framework (currently Claude Code). Where rules are naturally framework-agnostic (build commands, coding conventions, architecture), express them portably. Don't hobble the primary tool for the sake of frameworks that aren't in use.\n4. **Capture decisions, not just implementations** — ADRs or equivalent so future agents and humans know *why*, not just *what*\n5. **Enforcement over documentation** — rules that matter must be enforced mechanically (CI, hooks, branch protection), not just written down\n6. **Radical simplicity** — resist adding process, files, or tools unless the pain they solve is concrete and demonstrated\n\n## What's been done\n\n### Research (3,019 lines, 6 appendices)\n\nComprehensive technology research on `feature/issue-249` at `.agent/work-plans/RESEARCH_ISSUE-249.md`. Covers command runners, AGENTS.md sta