ent work.\n\n- [ ] **Shared instruction content: AGENTS.md, CLAUDE.md restructuring, or both** — Principle #3 says optimize for Claude Code but express naturally portable rules portably. The questions: which rules *are* naturally framework-agnostic (build commands, coding conventions, architecture)? Is there enough portable content to justify a separate AGENTS.md, or is it small enough to maintain in each framework file? Should CLAUDE.md be restructured as a \"map\" (~150 lines, §E3) regardless of whether AGENTS.md is created? Should the Always/Ask/Never taxonomy (§D5) be adopted? These are coupled decisions — the answer to one constrains the others.\n\n- [ ] **Simplify Makefile or replace with `just`** — The research recommends `just` (§1a), but this is a tool choice that adds a new dependency and affects daily workflow. The `just-mcp` angle (§F2.3) adds a consideration: it would make workspace commands accessible to any MCP-compatible agent. But the current Makefile with self-documenting patterns (§2) may be sufficient if the team prefers zero new dependencies.\n\n- [ ] **Consolidate and reduce documentation overlap** — Depends on what happens with the instruction file restructuring above. The 24 markdown files have documented overlaps (§5), but the consolidation strategy flows from the AGENTS.md/CLAUDE.md decisions. Can't be done independently.\n\n- [ ] **Evaluate MCP servers for ROS 2 workflows** — ROSBag MCP server, ROS 2 Robot Control MCP server, and potentially a custom workspace MCP server (§F2.3). Less a design question, more a \"is this useful for our actual workflow\" question. Depends on whether bag files and runtime inspection are part of the development loop.\n\n### Design considerations captured (in comments)\n\n- **Upstream contribution mode**: How PR templates and ADRs work when the workspace wraps someone else's project (e.g., contributing to nav2 through a fork). Workspace-layer infrastructure works naturally in both \"my project\" and \"upstream contribution\" modes.\n\n### How discussion items proceed\n\nEach discussion item should be resolved through conversation (on this issue or dedicated sub-issues). When a decision is reached, capture it as an ADR and then create a sub-issue for implementation. The enforcement question and the instruction file restructuring are the most foundational — they affect several other items.\n\n## Related issues\n\nThe research cross-references several open issues that overlap with this effort (§9). As work progresses, those issues may be absorbed, closed as duplicates, or kept as independent tasks that align with the direction here.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1772044630,"nonce":"z9PSgS1oYsz7Nax+lfnZFy3YCHc=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lAHOQ241x87so-6xzqX_C3o"},"target":"efb04c7efcf7f3b3327b856768c4da222682c6df50c82b27a8a34893f0240148","message":"## Problem\n\nThis workspace has grown through many small, isolated fixes. Each solved a real problem, but without a shared direction the result is accumulated complexity: overlapping scripts, duplicated documentation, and design decisions buried in issue comments where they get accidentally reverted.\n\nThe fix isn't a comprehensive redesign — it's establishing the direction that was missing, then improving incrementally with that direction guiding each step.\n\n## Vision\n\nA workspace that is:\n- **Simple to use** — a small number of clear entry points, not 42 scripts\n- **Self-documenting** — the structure and tooling explain themselves\n- **Durable** — design decisions are captured where they won't be lost or silently reverted\n- **Sustainable** — improvements continue naturally, not as periodic large rework efforts\n\n## Progress\n\nProgress is tracked on [Draft PR #257](https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/pull/257), which accumulates work via focused sub-PRs. Discussion of specific deliverables and next steps happens there.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1771624731,"nonce":"psn2t5HUhEqpQfpl2YoTbkmWoKY=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87qrziV","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3937351829"},"message":"I was still brainstorming with an agent when it got time to leave, so I quickly asked it to post it as needing further consideration. I still want to question and ponder deeply about the items in this issue. \nThe idea of the readme containing everything concisely is something I'm considering, but I certainly want to think about it more and get an idea of the impact it works have on it and related files. \nAlso, the switch to duplicating the instructions per framework was on purpose to reduce compromise as frameworks might prefer different ways of having instructions layed out. This is an example of an improvement that is at risk of accidentally getting reverted.\nI hate to suggest adding a new file, but maybe we need a central architecture document that would need to be consulted when an issue is considered, when a plan is made, and updated if needed when an issue is implemented.\nThis more robust and big picture approach should be used for the workspace and the project.","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1771861762,"nonce":"YWOuHCL++f5+Le3DaoMBkJxnQIg=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lALOQ241x87qrziVzptc5Eg"},"target":"2db075cd2c56dbb1c621eadf2ae9c3de879faf3f1dcad07883b684373107dd9a","message":"(Original message has been updated since I wrote this)\n\nI was still brainstorming with an agent when it got time to leave, so I quickly asked it to post it as needing further consideration. I still want to question and ponder deeply about the items in this issue. \nThe idea of the readme containing everything concisely is something I'm considering, but I certainly want to think about it more and get an idea of the impact it works have on it and related files. \nAlso, the switch to duplicating the instructions per framework was on purpose to reduce compromise as frameworks might prefer different ways of having instructions layed out. This is an example of an improvement that is at risk of accidentally getting reverted.\nI hate to suggest adding a new file, but maybe we need a central architecture document that would need to be consulted when an issue is considered, when a plan is made, and updated if needed when an issue is implemented.\nThis more robust and big picture approach should be used for the workspace and the project.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1771629514,"nonce":"V4lRMbl6wUC+2blyDxRxXUu00Ss=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87qswGY","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3937599896"},"message":"From a chat with Claude Code Agent...\n\nI'm Claude Code Agent, running on the Claude Opus 4.6 model.\nIf you're referencing me in a GitHub comment, the standard signature from the project's conventions would be:\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`\nThe research file is at .agent/work-plans/RESEARCH_ISSUE-249.md on branch claude/research-issue-technologies-70lUL.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1771779516,"nonce":"5iAZ+KMSb3/ZpcpkzLSnP/1FjKk=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87q7HkP","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3941366031"},"message":"This seems relevant if not anyway covers in the research paper. https://openai.com/index/harness-engineering/","files":null},{"type":2,"timestamp":1771861179,"nonce":"hSPJdkIZIfgaqVo2vswjcWMSRPM=","metadata":{"github-id":"RTE_lADOQ241x87so-6xzwAAAAVbONRE"},"title":"Workspace rework: establish direction and improve incrementally","was":"Workspace rework: establish direction and improve incrementally"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1771884250,"nonce":"aWoynqqAYRNDWvHCymRMOuHtLkk=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87rS0so","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3947580200"},"message":"# Agentic Coding Landscape — February 2026\n\nResearch scan of latest agentic coding blogs, repos, and emerging developments relevant to our workspace.\n\n---\n\n## Validation: We're Ahead of the Curve\n\nOur workspace architecture anticipated several patterns that are now becoming industry standard:\n\n- **Git worktree isolation** is now the recommended approach for multi-agent coding (blog posts, guides, and tools like `ccswarm`, `agentree`, and `git-worktree-runner` all converge on this)\n- **Issue-first policy** aligns perfectly with GitHub's new Agentic Workflows (see below)\n- **CLAUDE.md conventions** — the industry is converging on `AGENTS.md` as a cross-platform standard. Our CLAUDE.md is well-structured by current best practices\n\n---\n\n## High-Impact Developments\n\n### 1. Claude Code Agent Teams (Experimental)\nMultiple Claude Code instances coordinate as a team — a lead agent spawns teammates, each gets its own context window, and they communicate via a mailbox system. Enable with `CLAUDE_CODE_EXPERIMENTAL_AGENT_TEAMS=1`.\n\n**Patterns**: Leader/swarm/pipeline/watchdog. Best for parallel work on separate packages.\n**Our fit**: Our worktree infrastructure already supports the isolation layer. Agent teams would add the coordination layer on top.\n\n### 2. GitHub Agent HQ + Agentic Workflows (February 2026)\nGitHub now lets you run Claude, Codex, and Copilot side-by-side on the same issue. Agentic Workflows (technical preview) let you define automation in **Markdown** instead of YAML — AI agents figure out execution.\n\n**Use cases**: automated issue triage, CI failure investigation, documentation sync, test coverage improvement.\n**Our fit**: Our issue-first, PR-based workflow maps directly to this model.\n\n### 3. Model Context Protocol (MCP) — Now Industry Standard\nMCP was donated to the Linux Foundation's new **Agentic AI Foundation** (Dec 2025). It's the universal protocol for connecting AI agents to tools/data. Thousands of community servers exist.\n\n**Key for us**:\n- **ROSBag MCP Server** ([arXiv:2511.03497](https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.03497)) — natural language queries over ROS bag files\n- **ROS 2 Robot Control MCP Server** — standardized agent access to ROS 2 topics/services\n- We could build a custom MCP server exposing colcon commands, topic inspection, and workspace validation\n\n### 4. Agent Harness Pattern (Anthropic Engineering)\nThe \"Initializer + Coder\" pattern for long-running agents: a short-lived agent sets up the task, a long-running agent reads progress files (TODO.md), completes steps, updates state, commits, exits. Each session maintains continuity through persistent state.\n\n**Our fit**: Our worktree scripts + git-based progress tracking already implement this pattern. [Anthropic's engineering blog](https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/effective-harnesses-for-long-running-agents) codifies what we're doing.\n\n---\n\n## ROS 2–Specific Frameworks Worth Evaluating\n\n| Framework | Source | What It Does |\n|-----------|--------|-------------|\n| **ROSA** | NASA JPL ([github](https://github.com/nasa-jpl/rosa)) | Natural language interaction with ROS 1/2 systems — inspect, diagnose, operate robots |\n| **RAI** | RobotecAI ([github](https://github.com/RobotecAI/rai)) | Vendor-agnostic agentic framework for Physical AI, built on ROS 2 |\n| **ROS-LLM** | Auromix ([github](https://github.com/Auromix/ROS-LLM)) | LLM-based code generation for robot behaviors (sequences, behavior trees, state machines) |\n| **EmbodiedAgents** | Automatika ([docs](https://automatika-robotics.github.io/embodied-agents/)) | Production-grade framework for deploying Physical AI on real robots via ROS 2 |\n\n---\n\n## Trending Repos \u0026 Tools\n\n| Repo | Stars | Why It Matters |\n|------|-------|---------------|\n| **OpenHands** (formerly OpenDevin) | 65k+ | Leading open-source AI agent, LLM-agnostic |\n| **Claude Code** | 51.7k | Our primary tool — now has hooks, skills marketplace (1,341 skills), agent teams |\n| **OpenCode** | 50k | Open-source alternative gaining fast (+1,852 stars/day) |\n| **mini-swe-agent** | Active | 100 lines of Python, 65-74% on SWE-bench Verified — radical simplicity |\n| **awesome-claude-code** | Community | 75+ repos covering skills, hooks, plugins, orchestrators |\n| **ccswarm** | Active | Multi-agent orchestration using Claude Code + git worktree isolation |\n\n---\n\n## Claude Code Hooks (Underutilized by Us)\n\nHooks are shell commands that fire at lifecycle points (PreToolUse, PostToolUse, Stop). We could add:\n\n- **PreToolUse**: Enforce worktree usage (block edits to main tree files — currently handled by env.sh, but hooks add defense-in-depth)\n- **PostToolUse**: Auto-run `colcon test` after code changes, validate `package.xml`, run formatters\n- **PostToolUse**: Check that AI signature is present in PR/issue bodies\n\nConfigure in `.claude/settings.json` (project-level, committable).\n\n---\n\n## Industry Context Numbers\n\n- Agentic coding market: $550M → $4B in one year\n- 57% of companies run AI agents in production (Jan 2026)\n- Engineers integrate AI into 60% of work, but fully delegate only 0-20% of tasks\n- **40% quality deficit** projected — more code enters the pipeline than reviewers can validate\n- Gartner: 1,445% surge in multi-agent system inquiries (Q1 2024 → Q2 2025)\n\n---\n\n## Suggested Next Steps (by priority)\n\n1. **Evaluate Claude Code hooks** — low effort, high guard-rail value. Add PostToolUse hooks for formatting/linting after edits.\n\n2. **Try ROSBag MCP server** — if we work with bag files, this enables natural language log analysis directly from Claude Code sessions.\n\n3. **Experiment with Agent Teams** — on a non-critical multi-package feature, try `CLAUDE_CODE_EXPERIMENTAL_AGENT_TEAMS=1` with one agent per package in separate worktrees.\n\n4. **Watch GitHub Agentic Workflows** — currently in technical preview. When stable, it could automate our issue triage and CI failure investigation.\n\n5. **Evaluate ROSA (NASA JPL)** — natural language interface for ROS 2 system inspection. Could be valuable for operators who aren't developers.\n\n6. **Consider AGENTS.md compatibility** — the industry is converging on this as a cross-platform standard. We could add a symlink or maintain both files for future-proofing with other AI tools.\n\n---\n\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772008255,"nonce":"XyFWe7tpNdqKWIdtBK2Pd4uHZTc=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87r5Kr_","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3957631743"},"message":"Is this relevant to us or too focused on GitHub? \nhttps://github.blog/ai-and-ml/generative-ai/multi-agent-workflows-often-fail-heres-how-to-engineer-ones-that-dont/","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772036381,"nonce":"fqssndMhPoxQleJuLcuzVWVDSJo=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87sDzwv","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3960421423"},"message":"This has been reviewed and incorporated into the research document. The key findings are captured in Appendix F (§F7) of `.agent/work-plans/RESEARCH_ISSUE-249.md` on the feature branch, covering multi-agent engineering patterns from GitHub's failure analysis. The most relevant takeaways for us:\n\n- **Deterministic scaffolding** (structured handoffs, not free-form delegation) — aligns with our worktree isolation + issue-first approach\n- **Failure modes** (infinite loops, context loss, cascading errors) — validates our atomic-commit and single-issue-per-worktree patterns\n- **The \"good enough\" principle** — supports our incremental approach over big-bang redesigns\n\nThe landscape comment above (Feb 23) also references this under \"Industry Context Numbers\" with the 40% quality deficit projection.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772037507,"nonce":"KPgXodooKoYC32y98MRy/1lMYSM=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87sEPRy","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3960534130"},"message":"## Proposed guiding principle #7: Workspace improvements cascade to projects\n\n**Workspace infrastructure improvements should flow downstream to project repos when applicable.**\n\nWhen we invest in improving workflow quality — PR templates, CI patterns, hooks, documentation standards, coding conventions — the benefit shouldn't stop at the workspace repo boundary. If an improvement is general enough to apply to project repos (e.g., `unh_marine_autonomy`), it should be designed with that portability in mind and propagated to those repos as part of the same effort.\n\nThis doesn't mean forcing workspace conventions on projects. It means:\n- When designing a new workflow feature, ask \"does this also apply to project repos?\"\n- If yes, design it to be portable from the start rather than retrofitting later\n- The workspace repo serves as the reference implementation; project repos adopt what fits\n\nThis complements principle #3 (primary framework first, portability where free) — #3 is about portability across *agent frameworks*, this is about portability across *repos in the project*.\n\n**Practical implication for the PR template task**: the template should be designed as a reference that lives in the workspace and is explicitly copied/adapted into project repos, rather than being workspace-specific from the start.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772040876,"nonce":"yb08NpkTKfGoZB7HWDrSwiL9COs=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87sFbh6","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3960846458"},"message":"## Design consideration: PR templates and ADRs in upstream contribution mode\n\nDiscussion about how PR templates and ADRs work when the workspace wraps someone else's project (e.g., contributing to nav2 through a fork).\n\n### The scenario\n\nA manifest/workspace repo is created to work on an upstream project. You want your own process infrastructure (PR templates, ADRs) without polluting the upstream repo.\n\n### How it works\n\n**PR template on your fork**: `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md` on the fork applies when creating PRs *from* the fork. When opening a PR against upstream, GitHub uses the *upstream's* template (if any), not yours. So the fork's template helps during development and self-review but doesn't interfere with upstream. Never push `.github/` upstream.\n\n**ADRs live in the workspace/manifest repo, not the fork**: Decisions about *how you work with* the upstream project — \"we chose to fork package X rather than overlay it,\" \"we wrap behavior tree nodes rather than modifying them\" — are integration strategy decisions. Those belong in the workspace repo. The fork should hold only changes intended for upstream contribution.\n\n### Why this matters for the PR template design\n\nThis validates designing PR templates and ADR patterns to live at the workspace layer. If they're workspace-level infrastructure:\n- **\"My project\" mode**: workspace holds process infrastructure, project repo holds project-specific ADRs — works naturally\n- **\"Upstream contribution\" mode**: workspace holds all process infrastructure and integration ADRs, fork holds only upstream-bound changes — also works naturally\n\nIf these patterns were tightly coupled to the project repo, the upstream contribution mode would be awkward.\n\nThis is still a conceptual mode of operation, captured here so it informs design decisions rather than getting lost.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1772144091,"nonce":"IAWy4ry4U3Riah68ibKKu9WXJSY=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOQ241x87smn3f","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/249#issuecomment-3969547743"},"message":"## Progress Summary (Feb 2026)\n\n### Phase 1: Foundation — Complete ✓\n\nPR #257 was merged (48 commits, 7 sub-PRs). All foundational work:\n\n| Sub-PR | Deliverable |\n|--------|-------------|\n| #253 | 6 ADRs capturing existing design decisions |\n| #254 | Script \u0026 Makefile intent recovery (documented purpose of all scripts) |\n| #255 | Research digest on simplification patterns |\n| #258 | PR and ADR templates |\n| #259 | Guiding principles document |\n| #260 | ADR-0005: Layered enforcement strategy |\n| #262 | AGENTS.md as shared instruction file (ADR-0006) |\n\n### Phase 2: Actual Simplification — Not Started\n\nThe two issues that do the real simplification are both still open:\n\n- **#263 — Simplify scripts and Makefile interface**: Still 34 scripts and 19+ Makefile targets. No consolidation, dead code removal, or entry point reduction yet.\n- **#264 — Consolidate and reduce documentation overlap**: Still 8 top-level `.md` files, 5 `.agent/*.md` docs, 6 knowledge files. CLAUDE.md is still large inline rather than a ~150-line map.\n\nLower priority open issues spun off from this work:\n- #265 — CI enforcement checks\n- #266 — Evaluate MCP servers for ROS 2 workflows\n\n### Where to Resume\n\nPick up #263 or #264. Both are unblocked and well-scoped with prior research already done (intent recovery in `.agent/work-artifacts/issue-252-script-intents.md`, research digest from #255). The direction and principles are established — what remains is executing the simplification.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}